    <div class="artwork__inner">
        

<dl class="specification-list">

        <dt>Identification and Creation</dt>
        <dd>
          <dl>
            <dt>Object Number</dt>
            <dd>1943.889</dd>

                            <dt>People</dt>
                <dd>
                                                                 <a href=https://www.harvardartmuseums.org/collections/person/28171>Pierre-Paul Prud'hon</a>, French                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                          (Cluny 1758 - 1823 Paris)
                                            <br>
                                    </dd>
            
                            <dt>Title</dt>
                <dd>The Cruel One Laughs at the Tears Which It Causes To Be Shed</dd>
            
                                                                                                                                                                                                  <dt>Other Titles</dt>
                    <dd>
                                                                                                                                      Original Language Title: Le Cruel rit des pleurs qu'il fait verser                                                                        </dd>
                            
                            <dt>Classification</dt>
                <dd>Drawings</dd>
                                        <dt>Work Type</dt>
                <dd>
                                                            drawing                                                      </dd>
                                        <dt>Date</dt>
                <dd>1793</dd>
                                                                <dt>Culture</dt>
                <dd>French</dd>
                            <dt>Persistent Link</dt>
                <dd><a href="https://hvrd.art/o/296880">https://hvrd.art/o/296880</a></dd>
          </dl>
        </dd>

        
                <dt>Physical Descriptions</dt>
        <dd>
          <dl>
                          <dt>Medium</dt>
              <dd>Black chalk and black crayon on white antique laid paper</dd>
            
           
           
                          <dt>Dimensions</dt>
              <dd>actual: 24.5 x 32.3 cm (9 5/8 x 12 11/16 in.)</dd>
            
            
            
            
            
                          <dt>Inscriptions and Marks</dt>
              <dd>
                                  <ul class="unstyled-list">
                    
                                                                  <li data-a="2">
                          watermark: Fleur-de-lis atop a plain shield with a bend
                        </li>
                                          
                    
                                      </ul>
                              </dd>
            
          </dl>
        </dd>
        
                  <dt>Provenance</dt>
          <dd>Jean-Baptiste Martial Poulain; his sale, G. J. Constantin, Paris, December 19, 1803, no. 145 (as "Le cruel rit des pleurs qu'il fait verser; dessin précieux, à la pierre noire"; Fr 281); Barthélemy Roger; his sale, Mannheim, Paris, December 23-28, 1841, no. 139 (Fr 360); Constantini, by 1874 at least until 1879; anonymous sale (Constantini's, according to Guiffrey 1924, no. 19), Hôtel Drouot, Paris, room 3, April 15, 1882, no. 71 (as "L'Amour vainqueur"); purchased at that sale by Mme Poiret (Fr 1,000); Robert Hoe; his sale, American Art Association, New York, February 15-March 3, 1911, no. 3228; Richard Ederheimer Print Cabinet, New York, December 1913; anonymous sale, Paris, Hôtel Drouot, April 1, 1914, no. 89 (Fr. 1,000); Lilly Lawlor, Paris, 1927, acquired from her through Martin Birnbaum by Grenville L. Winthrop, July 1927 ($2,700), his bequest to the Fogg Art Museum, 1943.</dd>
        
        
        
        <dt>Acquisition and Rights</dt>
        <dd>
          <dl>
                          <dt>Credit Line</dt>
              <dd>Harvard Art Museums/Fogg Museum, Bequest of Grenville L. Winthrop</dd>
            
            
                          <dt>Accession Year</dt>
              <dd>1943</dd>
            
            <dt>Object Number</dt>
            <dd>1943.889</dd>

                          <dt>Division</dt>
              <dd>European and American Art</dd>
            
                          <dt>Contact</dt>
              <dd><a href="mailto:am_europeanamerican@harvard.edu"><span>am_europeanamerican@harvard.edu</span></a></dd>
                                      <dd>THIS WORK MAY NOT BE LENT BY THE TERMS OF ITS ACQUISITION TO THE HARVARD ART MUSEUMS.</dd>
                   		  <dd>The Harvard Art Museums encourage the use of images found on this website for personal, noncommercial use, including educational and scholarly purposes. To request a higher resolution file of this image, please submit an <a href="https://www.harvardartmuseums.org/imagerequest"><span>online request.</span></a></dd>
          </dl>
        </dd>

        
                  <dt>Publication History</dt>
          <dd>
                                        <p>
                                              Jacques-Philippe Voïart, <em>Notice historique sur la vie et les ouvrages de P.P. Prud'hon, peintre membre de la Légion-d'honneur et de l"institut</em>, Firmin Didot, Boulland et Cie (Paris, 1824), pg. 13
                             </p>
                                                      <p>
                                              Charles Blanc, <em>Le trésor de la curiosité (2 vols.)</em>, Vve. J. Renouard (Paris, 1857-1858), pg. 217
                             </p>
                                                      <p>
                                              Théodore Michel Lejeune, <em>Guide théorique et pratique de l’amateur de tableaux (3 vols.)</em>, Vve. J. Renouard (Paris, 1864-1865), vol. 1, pg. 315
                             </p>
                                                      <p>
                                              Charles Clément, <em>Prud'hon; sa vie, ses oeuvres et sa correspondance</em>, Didier et cie. (Paris, 1872), pp. 199, 206, 376
                             </p>
                                                      <p>
                                              Edmond de Goncourt, <em>Catalogue raisonné de l'oeuvre peint, dessine et grave de P. P. Prud'hon</em>, Rapilly (Paris, France, 1876), pg. 138
                             </p>
                                                      <p>
                                              B. Tailhades, "L'oeuvre de Prud'hon" [omissions and errors in Goncourt 1876], <em>La Chronique des arts et de la curiosité</em>, Bureaux de la Gazette des beaux-arts (Paris, November 10, 1877), pg. 329
                             </p>
                                                      <p>
                                              <em>Original Drawings by Old Masters</em>, checklist, R. Ederheimer Print Cabinet (New York, 1913), pg. 48, no. 93 repr.
                             </p>
                                                      <p>
                                              Jean Guiffrey, <em>L'oeuvre de P. P. Prud'hon</em>, A. Colin (Paris, France, 1924), pp. 9-10, no. 19 (and p. 21, following no. 52, for the 1882 sale)
                             </p>
                                                      <p>
                                              Martin Birnbaum, <em>The Last Romantic</em> (New York, NY, 1960), pg. 199
                             </p>
                                                      <p>
                                              James H. Slayman, "The Drawings of Pierre-Paul Prud'hon: A Critical Study" (1970), University of Wisconsin, Madison, pp. 25-27, 256, pl. 15
                             </p>
                                                      <p>
                                              Agnes Mongan, <em>David to Corot: French Drawings in the Fogg Art Museum</em>, Harvard University Press (Cambridge, MA, 1996), cat. no. 295, repr.
                             </p>
                                                      <p>
                                              Sylvain Laveissière, "À quel siècle Prud'hon appartient-il?", <em>Pierre-Paul Prud'hon: actes du colloque organisé au musée du Louvre par le service culturel, le 17 novembre 1997</em>, ed. Sylvain Laveissière, La documentation française, Musée du Louvre (Paris, (1997) 2001), pg. 211
                             </p>
                                                      <p>
                                              Philippe Bordes, "Un graveur disponsible, Jacques-Louis Copia", <em>Pierre-Paul Prud'hon: actes du colloque organisé au musée du Louvre par le service culturel, le 17 novembre 1997</em>, ed. Sylvain Laveissière, La documentation française, Musée du Louvre (Paris, (1997) 2001), pg. 113
                             </p>
                                                      <p>
                                              Sylvain Laveissière, <em>Pierre-Paul Prud'hon [Prud'hon ou le rêve du bonheur]</em>, exh. cat., Metropolitan Museum of Art / Harry N. Abrams, Inc. [Réunion des Musées Nationaux] (New York, NY and Paris, France, 1997), under no. 32, fig. 32a
                             </p>
                                                      <p>
                                              Sylvain Laveissière, <em>Prud'hon ou le rêve du bonheur</em>, exh. cat., Réunion des Musées Nationaux (Paris, France, 1997), under no. 32, fig. 32a
                             </p>
                                                      <p>
                                              Sylvain Laveissière, <em>Prud'hon: Le Cabinet des Dessins</em>, Flammarion (Paris, France, 1997), p. 28 and color repr. p. 29
                             </p>
                                                      <p>
                                              Alvin L. Clark, Jr., "Un grand collectionneur américain de dessins français: Grenville L. Winthrop et les oeuvres de Pierre-Paul Prud'hon au Fogg Art Museum", <em>Pierre-Paul Prud'hon: actes du colloque organisé au musée du Louvre par le service culturel, le 17 novembre 1997</em>, La documentation française, Musée du Louvre (Paris, 2001), pp. 177-202, p. 179, fig. 1, repr.
                             </p>
                                                      <p>
                                              Elizabeth Guffey, <em>Drawing an Elusive Line: The Art of Pierre-Paul Prud'hon</em>, University of Delaware Press/ Associated University Presses (Newark (DE) and London, 2001), pp. 81, 89-91, fig. 53, repr. (caption error: reproduction of Fogg drawing, not engraving after it)
                             </p>
                                                      <p>
                                              Stephan Wolohojian, ed., <em>A Private Passion: 19th-Century Paintings and Drawings from the Grenville L. Winthrop Collection, Harvard University</em>, exh. cat., The Metropolitan Museum of Art and Yale University Press (U.S.) (New York, 2003), cat. no. 101, repr. (color), p. 30
                             </p>
                                                      <p>
                                              Louis-Antoine Prat, <em>Le dessin français au XIXe siècle</em>, Somogy Éditions d'Art (Paris, 2011), p. 110
                             </p>
                                    </dd>
        
                  <dt>Exhibition History</dt>
          <dd>
                          <p>
                              <em>Exposition des oeuvres de Prud'hon au profit de sa fille</em>, Ecole des Beaux-Arts, Paris, 05/04/1874 - 07/04/1874
                            </p>
                          <p>
                              <em>Exposition de dessins de maîtres anciens</em>, Ecole des Beaux-Arts, Paris, 05/01/1879 - 06/30/1879
                            </p>
                          <p>
                              <em>A Private Passion: 19th-Century Paintings and Drawings from the Grenville L. Winthrop Collection, Harvard University</em>, The Metropolitan Museum of Art, New York, 10/23/2003 - 01/25/2004
                            </p>
                      </dd>
        
        

        
      
      
        
